Guided Exercise Summary: Project and Cluster Quotas (OpenShift)
1️⃣ Purpose of the Exercise
This exercise demonstrates how resource usage in one namespace can affect the entire cluster and how ResourceQuota prevents a 
namespace from consuming excessive resources.
________________________________________
1. Initial Scenario (Without Quotas)
A deployment test is created that requests 1 CPU per pod.
oc create deployment test --image=hello-world-nginx
oc set resources deployment test --requests=cpu=1
When scaled to 8 replicas:
oc scale deployment test --replicas=8
Only 2 pods run, while others remain Pending because the cluster has insufficient CPU.
Error example:
FailedScheduling: Insufficient cpu
________________________________________
2. Impact on Other Namespaces
Because the selfservice-quotas project consumed most CPU, another namespace (test) cannot create pods requesting 1 CPU.
This shows:
👉 One namespace can block resources for others if no quotas exist.
________________________________________
3. Fix: Create ResourceQuota
Administrator creates a quota:
oc create quota one-cpu --hard=requests.cpu=1
This quota means:
Maximum CPU requests in this namespace = 1 CPU
Quota YAML example:
spec:
  hard:
    requests.cpu: "1"
________________________________________
4. Effects of ResourceQuota
Case 1: Scaling deployment
If test deployment tries to scale to 8 replicas:
❌ Not allowed
Error:
exceeded quota: one-cpu
________________________________________
Case 2: Deployment without CPU request
A new deployment test-2 is created without CPU request.
❌ Pods are not created.
Error:
must specify requests.cpu
Because quota requires CPU requests to be specified.
________________________________________
5. Other Namespaces Still Work
Another project test is created.
Deployment test-3 requesting CPU:
oc set resources deployment test-3 --requests=cpu=1
✅ Pod runs successfully.
This proves:
👉 ResourceQuota only affects the namespace where it is applied.
________________________________________
6. Key Concepts Learned
ResourceQuota
Limits the total resources a namespace can use.
Example:
requests.cpu=1
memory=2Gi
pods=10
________________________________________
Benefits
ResourceQuota helps to:
✔ Prevent a namespace from consuming all cluster resources
✔ Protect other projects in the cluster
✔ Enforce fair resource usage
________________________________________
7. Important Commands
Login
oc login -u developer -p developer
Create project
oc new-project selfservice-quotas
Create deployment
oc create deployment test --image=image-name
Request CPU
oc set resources deployment test --requests=cpu=1
Scale deployment
oc scale deployment test --replicas=8
Create quota
oc create quota one-cpu --hard=requests.cpu=1
View quota
oc get quota one-cpu -o yaml
Check events
oc get events --sort-by .metadata.creationTimestamp
________________________________________
8. Final Conclusion
Without quotas:
•	One project can consume all cluster resources.
With quotas:
•	Each namespace has controlled resource limits.
•	Other namespaces remain unaffected.









Guided Exercise: Per-Project Resource Constraints (Limit Ranges)
Goal
Ensure that pods do not run without resource limits.
By default:
❌ Containers do NOT have CPU or memory limits
This is dangerous because a container can consume all cluster resources.
To solve this → LimitRange is used.
________________________________________
What is LimitRange?
A LimitRange sets default and maximum resource limits for containers inside a namespace.
It ensures that every container has:
•	Default requests
•	Default limits
even if the developer does not specify them.
Important:
⚠️ LimitRange works inside a namespace (project).
________________________________________
Step 1 – Start the Lab
Command:
lab start selfservice-ranges
Purpose:
•	Prepare lab environment
•	Ensure OpenShift cluster is ready
•	Create required lab resources
________________________________________
Step 2 – Login to OpenShift Web Console
Open browser:
https://console-openshift-console.apps.ocp4.example.com
Login with:
Field	Value
User	admin
Password	redhatocp
________________________________________
Step 3 – Create a Project
Navigate:
Home → Projects → Create Project
Create project:
Name: selfservice-ranges
Purpose:
Projects = namespaces in OpenShift
All workloads will run inside this namespace.
________________________________________
Step 4 – Create Deployment
Navigate:
Workloads → Deployments → Create Deployment
Fill:
Field	Value
Name	example
Image	registry.access.redhat.com/ubi8/httpd-24
Create deployment.
OpenShift automatically:
•	Creates 3 pods
•	Runs httpd container
________________________________________
Step 5 – Check Container Resources
Go to:
Workloads → Pods → Select Pod
Open container details.
You will see:
Resource Requests: -
Resource Limits: -
Meaning:
❌ No CPU request
❌ No memory request
❌ No CPU limit
❌ No memory limit
Containers are unrestricted.
________________________________________
Why is this Dangerous?
If container has no limit:
Example:
Cluster memory = 16GB
One container could consume:
16GB memory
This could crash other applications.
________________________________________
Step 6 – Create a LimitRange
Navigate:
Administration → LimitRanges
Click:
Create LimitRange
Template appears:
apiVersion: v1
kind: LimitRange
metadata:
  name: limits
spec:
  limits:
  - type: Container
    defaultRequest:
      memory: 256Mi
    default:
      memory: 512Mi
Meaning:
Setting	Value
Default memory request	256 Mi
Default memory limit	512 Mi
Create it.
________________________________________
Important Behavior
LimitRange only affects new pods.
Existing pods:
❌ Not modified.
That’s why the old deployment still has no limits.
________________________________________
Step 7 – Delete the Deployment
Navigate:
Workloads → Deployments
Delete:
example
This removes:
•	Deployment
•	ReplicaSet
•	Pods
________________________________________
Step 8 – Create Deployment Again
Create same deployment again.
Name: example
Image: registry.access.redhat.com/ubi8/httpd-24
OpenShift again creates 3 pods.
________________________________________
Step 9 – Check Container Resources Again
Go to:
Workloads → Pods → Pod → Container
Now you will see:
Memory Request: 256Mi
Memory Limit: 512Mi
Meaning:
LimitRange automatically added default values.
Even though developer did not specify resources.
________________________________________
Step 10 – Check Deployment YAML
Go to:
Workloads → Deployments → example → YAML
You will see:
resources: {}
Meaning:
Deployment did not define resources.
LimitRange adds limits only to pods, not to the deployment YAML.
Important concept:
Deployment spec remains unchanged
Pod spec gets modified
________________________________________
Step 11 – Check Pod Metrics
Navigate:
Pods → Pod → Metrics
You will see graph showing:
Metric	Value
Memory usage	~50 Mi
Memory request	256 Mi
Memory limit	512 Mi
Example:
Usage  = 50Mi
Request = 256Mi
Limit = 512Mi
Meaning:
Pod reserves 256Mi memory even though it uses only 50Mi.
________________________________________
Important Observation
If many pods run:
Example:
100 pods
Memory reserved:
256Mi × 100 = 25.6GB
Even if actual usage is smaller.
This can cause resource waste.
________________________________________
When to Use LimitRanges
LimitRanges help when:
✔ Developers forget to define limits
✔ Cluster admins want default policies
✔ Prevent unlimited containers
✔ Improve cluster stability
________________________________________
When to Be Careful
LimitRanges can cause:
•	Resource over-reservation
•	Quota issues
Example:
Namespace quota:
Memory request quota = 2GB
Each pod requests:
256Mi
Max pods allowed:
2GB / 256Mi = 8 pods
Even if cluster has more memory.
________________________________________
Finish Lab
Command:
lab finish selfservice-ranges
Purpose:
•	Clean resources
•	Prepare for next exercise
________________________________________
Key Concepts to Remember
Concept	Meaning
LimitRange	Defines default resource limits
Scope	Namespace
Affects	New pods only
Not modify	Deployment YAML
Adds	CPU/memory request and limit
________________________________________
Quick Difference (Exam Important)
Feature	Purpose
ResourceQuota	Limits total resources in namespace
LimitRange	Sets default/min/max resource per container
Example:
LimitRange → per container
ResourceQuota → per namespace

